Comment.value: First time PC speaks to Seeker.

value.0: Another lamb comes to join the slaughter, eh? Who are you?
That's none of your business. Trust Seeker when he tells you that you'd best be turnin' around and go back to your peaceful life.
They call me Seeker, and it's none of your business. Just go back the way you came and live out a long peaceful life.
Duty and nobility protect no one from death. My men died, though some of them were also full of noble ideals.
My men too had their gods of choice, yet where were those gods when their lives were stolen away.
Very well do I understand the life of a mercenary, for that is what my men are, or were.
And what would this quest be for?
Well then keep your secrets and keep your life. My men were on a quest too.
Experienced in the ways of war you might be, but so were my men.
We were twenty brave companions and we fought with valor, but that didn't stop thirteen of us from dying. Of the seven I have left, only two are still in fighting condition and they guard the camp.
I will not be responsible for sending more people to die on this thrice-damned quest.
Do I look like a simpleton, to be tricked so easily by words. Be off with you and your pestering questions.
Ah, then fine. Have it your way. If you want to rush to an early death, who am I to stand in your way?
<StartCheck>[Failure]</Start> If I thought you'd stand a chance I would agree with you, but I don't. You'll just die and haunt my dreams along with the others.
<StartCheck>[Success]</Start> I suppose what you say makes sense.
I called this quest thrice-damned because of the one who began it, the ones who betrayed it, and the ones who paid for it.
Listen instead of speaking, and it will come clear.
Lord Waldlaw, a baron in Battledale, sought to gain an alliance to protect his borders against an invading Zhent army.
He knew that he was outnumbered, and that reinforcements would arrive too late, so he acted out of desperation.
He had his brother, a mage, summon a powerful demon. The demon demanded that the Baron give him his only child as a sacrifice.
Yes, well, as it happens I agree. That is the one who began it. Making a deal with those foul creatures is dangerous at best.
Baron Waldlaw agreed to the deal and sent a couple of his soldiers to bring the child to the summoning room.
The soldiers had known the lad from when he was born, and while the father was willing to accept the demon's price, the soldiers thought it was too much.
The soldiers smuggled the child out through the kitchens and escaped the castle.
The demon was furious that the deal was broken and smashed a hole in the baron's wall before he disappeared. The Zhent army showed up the next day and slaughtered most of the baron's men.
Less than an hour later, the Zhent's turned and ran when outriders spotted another army headed for the castle.
The Baron didn't know that his cousin had heard about the Zhent army and was marching his army to join Waldlaw and drive them back.
It was too late to save the Baron, but the noble Lord Jasmir, Waldlaw's cousin found out about Waldlaw's heir from a kitchen serving girl.
He sent me and my company of free rangers to track and rescue Melorius, the heir to Castle Waldlaw and all its lands.
As I said at the first, there is a third part to this damned quest. Our company paid the price.
We are the third part of the damnation of this quest.
We tracked the soldiers to a cave, west of here. It's an old smuggler's cave, so a few people in the area know about it.
We thought the job was finished when we walked into the cave and saw the campfire burning. That's when those dark-skinned bastards hit us.
Bloody well right, drow.  Cold-blooded shadows that lept out and began cutting my men down before we had a chance to react.
Bloody drow elves is what I mean. Cold-blooded shadows that leapt out and began cutting my men down before we had a chance to react.
A group of us escaped their trap, but when we got out of the cave, spiders swarmed out of the trees. They took the rest of us as we fought our way out of the area.
Now we are seven, and there's no way we can go back in there. Four of my men aren't well enough to protect this area even.
The lad's uncle, the mage who summoned the demon, still lived, and he gave me this gem that contains a small portion of Melorius's life force.
As long as the gem is warm to the touch, the boy still lives. I don't know what dark purpose the drow have in mind for the boy, but I doubt he has long to live.
We're going to wait here until the gem grows cool, then return to the uncles and tell them the demon-elves killed the heir.
We get paid 200 for risking our lives. If we return the boy alive, we get paid an extra 500 gold. I won't face certain death for 500 gold.
Fine then. You'd better get out of here while you can. I have to wait for my men to heal and the boy to die.
Hopefully the drow won't come after us here.
You want to save the child, you go right ahead. We'll tell Lord Jasmir you died in the attempt when we tell him about the boy's death.
How dare you judge me! My men died trying to save a child who should have already died by his father's consent!
There is nothing we can do. The drow are too strong and we are too few. I won't throw my life away for such foolishness.
You want to save the child, you go right ahead. We'll tell Lord Jasmir you died in the attempt when we tell him about the boy's death.
In the unlikely chance you succeed, there's a 500 gold piece reward you are welcome to claim.
I'll even front the money, since I can claim the reward when I return the boy.
<StartCheck>[Failure]</Start> That ain't the way I work. You get nothin' from me until that boy shows up here alive.
<StartCheck>[Success]</Start> Yeah, I know how it goes. Here's 100 gold up front.
You might wanna go see the merchant over to the northeast. He's got some good stuff you might be interested in.
You can ask him that. Goodbye.
Good luck.
<StartCheck>[Failure]</Start> I already paid someone an advance. No more gold gets paid until that kid is back here alive.
We're off to return the lad... er... Baron Waldlaw back to his home. See you around, <FullName>.
So you're still alive, eh? What do you want from me?
You did it! Incredible, I truly thought you were a dead <man/woman>.
Here is your reward. I shall escort the new Baron Waldlaw back to his castle immediately.
And where were you when I needed rescuing?
Oh... uh... my men were wounded, so we stayed here to protect them and to guard <FirstName>'s way out.
Well, I have my doubts, but I suppose I live, so all is forgiven. Isn't that magnanimous of me?
Ah, the loyalty money buys. What a sad state of affairs.
I shall be sure to remember your deeds, <FullName>. Maybe you will consider coming to work for me someday.
If you really want to succeed in this world, you need to use every resource at your disposal. Or something like that.
Good for you. I'd offer you a hero cookie, but it appears I'm fresh out. I guess the drow must have eaten them. Poor, foolish Bessada.
Come Seeker. Time to go.
I have no time to answer your questions; I have important work to do elsewhere. Come along Seeker. We still have much to do.
Yes Master. We follow.
I hope to here about your exploits in the near future. Congratulations, <FirstName>.
Go west, over the bridge and follow the trail of dead corpses. You can't miss it.

Comment.value: spoken to Seeker, plot not accepted

value.0: This ain't no place for tourists. You'd better clear out of the area if you wanna survive.
Yeah, goodbye.
I told you this was none of your business, so why do you keep bugging me?
There be fight? Where be fight?
Slaughter? What are you talking about?
Me be <FirstName>. Who you be and who be dead?
My name is <FirstName>. Who are you and what slaughter are you talking about?
This be noble quest, maybe? Me know me duty be to do good. No mind danger one bit.
Surely there is a noble quest here that I might assist with. It is my duty to use my abilities to further any good deed, danger or no.
The gods make me wanderer in life; maybe them send me here to help you.
The gods set me on the path of a wanderer; perhaps I was led here to help you.
Me get paid to be in danger. Me no worry. You tell me what you need.
A powerful mercenary has nothing to worry about, if <he/she>'s capable. Tell me about your troubles, my good man.
Me on big quest and it lead me this way. Maybe part of me quest get done while me helps you.
I am on an important quest that has led me to this area. Though my quest is of paramount importance, perhaps in assisting you, I shall come closer to my goal.
That no be you business, it mine only.
That is none of your business.
Me promise not to tell no one. You no ask 'bout it no more, okay?
I am oath-bound to secrecy and may tell you no more.
Danger runs away from me when I fight. You's tell me 'bout you's troubles and me solve 'em.
I have stared death in the eye so often I have no fear of his bloody work. Now tell me about your troubles.
You no tell me, but me still go. Me might die cuz you no tell me what me fight, but me go no matter.
Keep your silence then, but still I will go. Too bad I must face unknown perils instead of knowing what to expect.
You tell me what go on, or me do job you enemy starts.
You will tell me what you were doing, or I shall finish what your enemies started.
What that mean "thrice-damned"? It make you swear three times?
What do you mean, "thrice-damned"?
<StartCheck>[Insight]</Start> You have obviously found defeat, both physically and mentally. If I die, what more have you lost?
<StartCheck>[Persuade]</Start> If you want to do you job, you use the tools you gots. Me can help you.
<StartCheck>[Persuade]</Start> If you really want your quest to succeed you need to use every resource at your disposal. I can help you.
Me all confused by that.
I have no idea what you're babbling about.
What you mean?
What do you mean?
Who he want ally with?
What kind of alliance did he seek?
Him make that deal?
And was that a trade he was willing to make?
Demon? Him stupid!
A demon? What a fool!
This be too long story. Get on with it.
This is taking too long, hurry it up.
Them be ones who betray?
So they're the ones who betrayed it?
Who be other army?
Who was the other army?
Him had only to fight for part of day before him could be saved.
You mean he only had to hold out for part of a day and reinforcements would have come?
You not be best choice for him to make.
Obviously he made a poor choice.
What happen to you?
So what happened to you?
There were drow in the cave?
Dark? What you mean?
Dark-skinned? What are you talking about?
What you think you do now?
What are you planning to do then?
You think boy be dead then?
Do you think the boy is dead then?
That be good idea. You get paid to do job anyways?
Well, that's probably the smartest thing to do. You get paid to do this job anyways?
Me not take chance of die for so little.
I don't think I'm interested in that much danger for so little gold.
Me risk neck for 500 gold. Me save boy and then get gold.
Well, I'm willing to take that chance. If I rescue the boy, I'll take the 500 gold.
You not know honor or duty or you at least try to save child.
A person with any understanding of duty would at least try to save the child.
You be big chicken! You no even gonna try to save kid?
You cowardly bastard. You'd let the child die without even trying to rescue him?
Father make mistake, not child. Other folk die to protect child, me no let them die for no reason!
You judge the child by his father's weakness, but others died trying to save the child and I won't let their sacrifice be in vain!
You know stuff that might help?
Anything else you can tell me that might help?
<StartCheck>[Persuade]</Start> Me need some gold now.
<StartCheck>[Persuade]</Start> I'll need to get some cash up front then.
What merchant be out here for?
What is a merchant doing out here?
Okay, thanks. Goodbye.
Here be kid.
Here's the kid.
<StartCheck>[Lie]</Start> Yeah, that be it. Me tell Seeker to wait here, cuz me not need him for rescue.
<StartCheck>[Lie]</Start> Um... yes. I didn't think I would need Seeker's help, so I told him to wait here for us.
You lie. You wait for Melorius to die. You think me die too.
You liar! You were waiting for Melorius to die. You thought I was dead too.
How you know me whole name?
How do you know my full name?
<StartCheck>[Insight]</Start> Enough of this charade! I think I know who you really are!
What happen here? Who you be for real?
What's going on here? Who or what are you really?
Where this cave be 'gain?
Where was this cave again?
Goodbye.
Me want help boy.
I want to try to save the boy.
Me need reminded what you do here again.
Tell me what you are here for again.
